    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. can u explain how it affects gradient descent specifically? like if the scales are way off, does it actually change the path the optimizer takes?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely; unequal scales cause gradient descent to converge inefficiently by forcing the model into an elongated, narrow valley of the loss surface. Instead of moving in straight, diagonal lines toward the minimum, the optimizer bounces back and forth along the axes, taking thousands of small gradient steps to cover the same distance it would take a single step on balanced features. This oscillation significantly slows down training and can cause instability, especially if the features have vastly different ranges like yours.",
      "source": "target",
